nsiders both 'canonical' and less well known Scottish writers, including Gaelic poets and mountaineering literature, Robert Louis Stevenson and John Muir, and contemporary authors Kathleen Jamie and John BurnsideThe first book to consider Scottish literature in the light of ecological and green thoughtEngages with a major topical issue and sets the study of Scottish writing within the broader context of international green approaches to literary studiesEncourages reflection on the links between literary studies and perspectives drawn from the disciplines of environmental history, anthropology, philosophy and cultural geography"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEcology in literaturey19th century. 0aScottish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aScottish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074863311140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748631988?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748631988423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748631988/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK